post_text:
Dear Parents,

Please consider joining WCS 2020-2021. We need you! Here are three great reasons you should apply to be a sub through EDUStaff.org:

1) It is a way for you to still play an active role in the school setting since we cannot allow volunteers or visitors.

2) You can sub exclusively at WCHS; WACC; Gateway; Lakeview; Edgewood; Claypool; Eisenhower; Harrison; Jefferson; Leesburg; Lincoln; Madison; or Washington.

You might choose one day a week. You might choose a couple of days a month.

3) You can make a little money while supporting YOUR child’s school.

With appreciation,

WCS

#wcsmission #ForwardTogether

post_text:
United Way is partnering with Warsaw Schools to launch START UNITED, a summer experience for 1,000 children who need a boost before the first day of school. This partnership provides an on-ramp for students who need to regain any momentum that has been lost since March. Routine is so important for kids. It gives them the security they need to explore and take risks. United Way is ready to take the first step in helping our kids reset their routines.

Read United matches volunteers with a classroom where they will share stories via Zoom call. United Way provides books and prompt cards. Volunteers read once a week for 15 minutes for 3 weeks. 100 volunteers are needed. Sign up at United Way’s website, https://www.unitedwaykosciusko.org/
Registration deadline is July 19th. #ForwardTogether #wcsmission #STARTUNITED

post_text:
WCS FREE SUMMER MEALS! Changes for July, 2020
Available to all children age 18 and under July 13 through August 6th Monday & Thursday from 2:00 – 4:00 PM Lakeview Middle School – 848 E Smith St., Warsaw (Use Geneva Street entrance and drive to back parking lot) Drive through pick up only – must be in line by 4:00 PM to receive meals. Registered children do not have to be present. Please Note: No Meals Monday, July 6.

Register Today for July Meals: www.wcsfoodandnutrition.org

MONDAYS July 13, 20, 27 and August 3: Pick up 3 days of meals and 1/2 gallon milk for each child

THURSDAYS July 16, 23, 30 and August 6: Pick up 4 days of meals and 1/2 gallon of milk for each child
Call 574-371-5086 or email questions to mfranks@warsawschools.org
#wcsmission #ForwardTogether
text:
WCS FREE SUMMER MEALS! Changes for July, 2020
Available to all children age 18 and under July 13 through August 6th Monday & Thursday from 2:00 – 4:00 PM Lakeview Middle School – 848 E Smith St., Warsaw (Use Geneva Street entrance and drive to back parking lot) Drive through pick up only – must be in line by 4:00 PM to receive meals. Registered children do not have to be present. Please Note: No Meals Monday, July 6.

Register Today for July Meals: www.wcsfoodandnutrition.org

MONDAYS July 13, 20, 27 and August 3: Pick up 3 days of meals and 1/2 gallon milk for each child

THURSDAYS July 16, 23, 30 and August 6: Pick up 4 days of meals and 1/2 gallon of milk for each child
Call 574-371-5086 or email questions to mfranks@warsawschools.org
#wcsmission #ForwardTogether

post_text:
Warsaw Community Schools’ Chief Technology Officer, Brad Hagg, was selected as a featured guest for Toggle Magazine. Brad Hagg was interviewed regarding the technology plan for WCS. Under Hagg’s leadership, Warsaw established a strong foundation with the 1:1 program for students and tech infrastructure to support the district goals.
Because of this foresight, Hagg and his team were quickly able to respond when COVID-19 changed everything! Student iPads were deployed, tech support was ready, WiFi hotspots supplemented by WiFi mobile locations were published, and eLearning became the way forward.
Thank you Brad Hagg and the Tech Team for all you did to prepare WCS students and teachers to rise to the challenge! #ForwardTogether #wcsmission
Great Photos + Read the Full Article: https://www.togglemag.com/case-studies/brad-hagg-warsaw-community-schools/

Welcome to the Building Trades House located at 2660 Muirfield Rd. Winona Lake, IN 46590.
This project was financed by Denny (Building Trades Advisory Committee Member) & Glenda Duncan.
Eric Taylor (Building Trades Instructor), along with multiple community cooperative firms, offered valuable hands-on experiences to assist the 8 second-year students and 13 first-year students as they enter various building trades as a career or when they become homeowners.

Good Morning Warsaw. Please join Dr. David Hoffert, WCS Superintendent, as he leads us in The Pledge of Allegiance and shares a message for our community.

I pledge Allegiance to the flag
of the United States of America
and to the Republic for which it stands,
one nation under God, indivisible,
with Liberty and Justice for all.

As we close 2019-2020, Warsaw Community Schools would like to express our heartfelt gratitude for all the support of parents, students, staff, and community. We wish you all a beautiful Memorial Day weekend and summer break.

Class of 2020, Congratulations! We’ll see you on June 5 for photos and on July 17 for graduation #wcsmission #forwardtogether

post_text:
Madeline Bowell, Emma Marsh, and Brittany Duncan are in the Class of 2021 at Warsaw Community High School. Nominated and selected to participate in the Kosciusko Youth Leadership Academy (KYLA), these three young ladies have learned about leadership and community service through classroom and hands-on training. Their chosen project was to design, create, and donate a customized piece of art to each of the Warsaw Community Schools elementary buildings. Last week, Jefferson, Leesburg and Eisenhower received theirs. Today, they delivered on that promise to Harrison, Washington, Madison, Lincoln, and Claypool.

Thank you Madeline, Emma, and Brittany for living the #wcsmission

post_text:
Last week, Warsaw Community Schools held their first milestone moment for seniors with curbside pickup of graduation regalia. The Graduation Taskforce for WCS has been working to finalize graduation plans for the Class of 2020. While following state directives, it is the goal of Warsaw Community Schools to hold an in-person graduation ceremony.

The date set forth is Friday, July 17, 2020 at 7:30 p.m. on the football field, observing social distancing guidelines. Please note, since this is an outdoor event, the first rain date would be Saturday July 18 at 7:30 p.m. and then July 19 at 7:30 p.m.

Further details regarding graduation and milestone moments for WCS seniors will be published on the Class of 2020 Forum on the district, high school, and WACC websites http://warsawschools.org and on social media accounts.

Tuesday THANK YOU goes out to ALL who work in the Ag Industry.
April Boggs, ELA Teacher at Lakeview Middle School offers a Tribute to Agriculture Workers

“My step-brother, Matt Firestone, works for Tom Farms. He puts in long hours to see that our community’s agriculture production keeps moving forward when everything else seems to be paused. He is the proud father of a two year old daughter, and a brand new baby girl. I know his wife and girls appreciate how he is out there doing his part to keep our economy running!”

For all who are part of the essential system of getting food from farm to table, we appreciate you! #wcsmission

In her own words, “I think it is fun to see one image of painting in the classroom with Art Basics early in the school year and also on autodesk sketchbook through eLearning tutorials I made through screen-o-matic! A lesson on negative and positive space plus on foreground, middle-ground, and background in landscapes!!!! Don't you want to go to this tropical paradise?!” Congratulations 7th graders: Alena Carboneau(deeper tones image); Lilia Gustafson (pink image); and Katelyn Brown(orange). Thank you Mrs. Keffaber for GROWING students.
Enjoy the beautiful weekend Warsaw :-) #wcsmission

Today, our THURSDAY THANK YOU belongs to all Emergency Workers
Shelby Beam, Lincoln Elementary School, offers a tribute to a few of our hometown heroes: Joel Beam, Mike Wilson, Carl Wireman, Layne Sumner, and K-9 Buddy.

“My husband, Police Captain Joel Beam, Warsaw Fire Department Chief Mike Wilson, Flight Medic Carl Wireman and Police Chaplain Layne Sumner make up a unique team called CISM, Critical Incident Stress Management.

This group has received training in trauma so that they can help and counsel all of our first responders as they respond to repeated trauma and deal with their feelings and emotions after tragic events. These men sit in on the hardest incidents with those who have experienced them and help them process and recover from what they have seen. It is long and hard work, but they run toward it in order to help those who help us on a daily basis. This is in addition to the hard frontline jobs these men maintain on their own.”

With a heartfelt thank you for all you do to make our community the best place to live, we offer our gratitude! #wcsmission

As we wrap up Autism Awareness Month, Mrs. Demopoulos would like to share a final book, Armond Goes to A Party: A book about Asperger's and Friendship by Nancy Carlson and her friend Armond Isaak.

Mrs. Demopoulos adds, "It has been so wonderful to share these books with you each week, about autism. I feel so blessed to go to work at Warsaw Community Schools and work with the wonderful staff. I get to be with the most amazing students each and every day. I hope you have enjoyed these books as much as I have enjoyed reading them to you."

Tip of the week:
Individuals with autism may have difficulty generalizing skills from one setting to another. An individual who has learned turn-taking in the classroom setting with peers, may not be able to take turns in the home setting with siblings. These individuals will need to be taught skills in multiple settings as well as with different people and activities/tasks.

post_text: Thank you Mrs. Beeson, Lakeview Middle School # wcsmission
shared_text:
United Way of Kosciusko County is with Warsaw Community Schools and Warsaw Community High School.
April 29 at 7:00 PM ·

Jean Beeson- Making Masks, Saving Lives

“I want the community to know I enjoy helping others in any way I can - from tech issues to medical needs,” Jean Beeson said. “I love this community. I’m so grateful to see everyone come together for the greater good.”

Jean has called Kosciusko County home for 48 years. She works for Warsaw Community Schools as Technology Specialist at Lakeview Middle School, as well as the Assistant Director for Warsaw High School Theater.

When United Way put out the call for volunteers to make masks, Jean was the first to volunteer. Now, Jean has a team of volunteer seamstresses she leads each week.

“With the onset of Covid-19, I saw an opportunity to do something,” Jean said. “This is a huge endeavor. United Way is counting on us to get the job done! I jumped at the chance to use my sewing skills and serve others. My hope is that each mask will protect a medical worker and their patients.”

To help purchase materials for masks, you can donate now at https://untdwy.org/3aTbEVHJean

Please keep in mind Honors students NEED to test to remain eligible for Honors, grades 9-11, per Indiana Department of Education.

shared_text:
United Way of Kosciusko County
April 18 at 10:00 AM ·

Meet Mike Castle - Keeping Our Children Safe

Mike was born in Warsaw. For the last 14 years, he's been a custodian for Warsaw Community High School.

“While we all wish that students were here, we’re taking this time to make sure that when they come back, this building is ready for them. They can count on that!” Mike said, “We are all working hard to get deep cleaning done and prioritize areas that have been hard to get to.”

“We can’t wait to get everyone back in school, but until then, we’re going to keep working to make this a great place for us all.”

To help children in need during the crisis, you can sponsor a Busy Bag by donating right now: https://unitedtoact.org/unitedwaykosciusko/children-in-need

The book this week for Autism Awareness Month is "My Brother is Autistic" by Jennifer Moore-Mallinos.
We hope you enjoy listening and learning about autism.
Our hope is that you take this information and grow your awareness of those individuals in our community.

Tip of the week:
Break tasks or activities down into smaller steps. Use pictures of the steps, model the steps, and say each step out loud to help the student/individual be successful.

Maria D Demopoulos, MA
Autism Resource Specialist

#wcsmission #autismawareness

April is Autism Awareness Month. Typically, Mrs. Demopoulos would be creating art projects with some of our students on the autism spectrum to display at Central Office, but decided to do something a bit different this year.

Each week, Mrs. Demopoulos will be reading a book to you about autism, and including a helpful tip. In her own words, "I hope you enjoy 'Looking after Louis' by Lesley Ely and Polly Dunbar."

Tip of the Week:
When speaking with individuals on the autism spectrum, keep your words simple. To get your point across, use as few words as possible. Using jargon, idioms, or sarcasm can be confusing for individuals on the autism spectrum, as they can take your words literally.

Thank you, Mrs. Demopoulos for your work to bring Autism Awareness through literature. #wcsmission

Get Ready for Monday: Enrichment Opportunity for Grades 6-12

WNIT Public Television - PBS Michiana and the WORLD Channel, in partnership with PBS LearningMedia, will begin broadcasting At Home Learning programs for grades 6-12 on Monday, March 30.

The programs will be available Monday through Friday from Noon to 5:00 p.m. These daily free-over-the-air broadcasts will feature the best in public media science, history, and other educational programming. WNIT plans to air this new broadcast locally on temporary channel 34.5 for the duration of the pandemic.

Please, rescan your televisions to recognize this new channel.
Note that 34.5 will only be available over the air by antenna.

*Please Share* #wcsmission

It’s the LAST Friday in March and we’re ready to wrap up eLearning for the week.
We leave you with this adorable photo and an update from the AMAZING Mrs. Wood, Special Education teacher at Lakeview Middle School.

Mrs. Wood and her “ K-9 Assistant Teacher” Murphy checked in with their students this week. On Monday and Tuesday, they provided help sessions for Math. On Wednesday and Thursday, it was English Language Arts. On Fridays, they support students in History, Science, and Electives.

Between sessions, this dynamic duo are reaching out to individual students to make sure they are getting their accommodations and support. Conferences with parents are happening through Google Meet.

It’s a full schedule, but TEAMWORK MAKES THE DREAM WORK!
Thank you Murphy and Mrs. Wood for ALL you are doing for WCS students! #wcsmission

post_text:
Warsaw Community Schools announces that Gina Courtois, Social-Emotional Learning Coordinator, will lead a Community Book Study to begin after Spring Break. The chosen book is “The Power of Showing Up: How Parental Presence Shapes who our Kids Become and How their Brains Get Wired” by authors Dan Siegel and Tina Payne Bryson. The first 50 to sign up will receive a free book.

Courtois recently had the opportunity to hear Dan Siegel speak. In her own words, “He was full of great information and ideas. In one of his sessions, he spoke about the power of relationships and mentioned his book “The Power of Showing Up.” In this book, Siegel and Payne articulate and quantify how to make parenting easier and better!”

To join this community book study, please complete the Google Form by April 3, 2020: https://bit.ly/WCSBookStudy

For resources and more information on Social-Emotional Learning, please go to https://www.smore.com/734b6 to follow Gina Courtois and to subscribe to monthly newsletters.

Any questions, please email Gina Courtois at gcourtois@warsawschools.org
#wcsmission

Wednesday, March 25: And we’re wrapping up another exciting eLearning day! It’s gorgeous - so let’s get some sunshine :-)
All across WCS, our teachers are taking on new challenges and retooling. You see, we are all students too! So three cheers to teachers who now have their own YOUTUBE channel, have dabbled with screencastify, have jumped into Google Hangouts, and have used their creative powers to deliver engaging content and connect with the students we all miss so much!
Meet Kami Toumey, Language Arts teacher at Edgewood Middle School. She has three adorable children who are her “practice” audience as she immerses herself in these new technologies. Today, her students met on a Google Hangout to discuss Edgar Allen Poe’s Black Cat and check in. In her words, “It was good to see and hear from them. The general consensus is - they all miss school!” Thank you Mrs. Toumey and all teachers who are doing their best to meet the needs of our WCS students #wcsmission

She’s giving her time and talents again to a new cause. In her own words, “When this Covid-19 virus broke out and the need for face masks spread, I wondered how I could help. Then I was contacted by Fabiola Nunez about sewing masks for a local nursing home. Her husband Berto Nunez is the administrator at Paddock Springs, which is located north of Warsaw. He was in need of 120 face masks for his employees. I was thrilled about helping folks in our local community! “ Thank you Mrs. Beeson for living the #wcsmission

shared_text:
Warsaw Community Schools added a new photo — at Lakeview Middle School.
March 24 at 4:09 PM · Warsaw, IN ·

With permission, WCS has UPLIFTING news to share: Ms. Perez, EL Teacher at Lakeview Middle School, finished chemotherapy! Here is a picture of her "ringing the bell" at the Cancer Treatment Center. It is a long tradition that chemo patients who finish their last treatment get to "ring the bell" in celebration! All the other patients still receiving chemo hear this and are encouraged...longing for their day to come when they get to "ring the bell." Next up, Ms. Perez will have surgery (April 28) and radiation. Stay strong Ms. Perez!

As we wrap up a week that we will never forget, we thank everyone for their support, generosity, and understanding. It truly is a community effort! We leave this week with an offer from WCHS teacher Mrs. Emily Gough. She’s here to assist with all levels of science from elementary up through AP Bio, Chem, or Environmental. She’s also tutored math elementary up through Algebra. Mrs. Gough is happy to answer any questions, or direct you to someone who can. She also wants to remind us all, “We WILL get through this!” #bettertogether 🧡
@ Warsaw Community High School P.S. Don’t you love her tech skills to make learning fun and “out of this world”?

post_text:
In light of Indiana Governor Eric Holcomb’s press release at 1:00 PM, Warsaw Community Schools will extend the closing of physical school buildings until May 1 in compliance with the executive order.

As previously messaged, Warsaw Community Schools and active student learning continues to stay open through eLearning lessons.

WCS will extend the current plan of a three-day eLearning week on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays while using Tuesdays and Thursdays as waiver days. From now until May 1, students will have the same educational opportunities that went into effect this week.

Additionally, WCS services provided by Food & Nutrition, Transportation, Technology, Teachers, and the WCS Nurse On-Call will also remain the same. Please see FAQs posted on the District Website.

WCS will continue to evaluate the situation and will communicate any changes as they become necessary. All updates will be posted on the District Website at warsawschools.org

Additionally, WCS services provided by Food & Nutrition, Transportation, Technology, Teachers, and the WCS Nurse On-Call will also remain the same. Please see FAQs posted on the District Website.

FAQ #18. What if I have a medical question about my child?

WCS Nurse On-Call

Who: WCS School Nurses
When: Mon - Fri 7:30 AM - 3 PM
How: Call WCHS (574) 371-5099 or WCS Central Office (574) 371-5098
Why: Call if you have a general medical question regarding a WCS student.

*Contact emergency services if the situation is critical - call 911 or your primary care physician. #wcsmission Please Share

Today is the first eLearning day! Teachers are working from home and that sometimes means that there is nobody around to take a photo of you...but if at first, you don’t succeed (with the selfie stick) try, try, and try again. Yep, we’re learning too:-)

Over the coming days, we’ll share a glimpse into what life is like for our amazing teachers as they plan, create, assign, check for understanding, re-teach, assess, and grade. They are here for you!

Meet Kaylynn Lampen, Department Leader for English Learners at WCHS. She has a great sense of humor, is incredibly kind, and spent Christmas in Bolivia. She recently got engaged - congrats Kaylynn and Brad! Ms. Lampen is here to help, to guide, to encourage, and to support! Here we go Tigers! Please Note: No selfie-stick was hurt during the three attempts to get a good photo:-) #wcsmission

http://bit.ly/Districtelearning
@ Warsaw Community High School

Teachers all across Warsaw Community Schools have been working diligently to plan for eLearning lessons. These fearless educators are going above and beyond again to create meaningful and engaging curriculum. They are doing what they do best and leading the way through unchartered territory.

Over the coming days, we’ll share a glimpse into what life is like for our amazing teachers as they plan, create, assign, check for understanding, re-teach, assess, and grade. They are here for you!

Meet Abbi Richcreek - she’s a PLTW teacher at Edgewood. Known for her generosity, grant writing skills, and love for horses, she’s here to kick start the first eLearning day...beginning on Wednesday, March 18th. Please Note: No technology was hurt during the making of this film:-) #wcsmission
eLearning Links to ALL WCS Schools: http://bit.ly/Districtelearning

post_text:
The Warsaw Area Career Center's Broadcasting Program is proud to announce another award winner from its TV II class. Congratulations to Logan Smith for his Second Place finish in the Animation Category at the Indiana Association of School Broadcasters Annual Contest. His animation "Conquering Fears" can be viewed at http://bit.ly/WACCAnimation

IASB Executive Director and University of Indianapolis Communication Instructor, Scott Uecker had this to say about this year's competition, "Every year it becomes more difficult to judge this competition, not just because we continue to have a record number of entries from an increasing number of schools and career centers, but because the quality of the student work is incredible. There's no doubt that the future of broadcasting is very bright when you see what the next generation of broadcast professionals is already doing. Congratulations to the students and their instructors for their amazing work."

So many people are asking: HOW CAN I HELP?
Bit.ly/WCSFAQS
Bit.ly/WCSFAQSSpanish
Boomerang Backpacks: There are two specific requests for help from the community:
1) Financial Donations
WCS buys food in bulk to provide the same items for each student each week and receive better pricing. Anyone willing to help can donate:
Online: Go to http://bit.ly/WCSBBDonation and specify “Warsaw Schools.”
By Mail: Send a check to Boomerang Backpacks 4616 E. Dupont Rd. Suite C, Fort Wayne IN 46825 and put “Warsaw Schools” on the memo line.

2) Volunteers
When: 2 PM, Thursdays (March 19, March 26, and April 2).
Where: Warsaw Community High School (Door #4 on the front, north side of the building).
Role: There are two roles: Screeners; Packers.
Sign Up Link: http://bit.ly/WCSBBVolunteer
Contact: Tracey Akers, Adult Coordinator for Warsaw Boomerang Backpack Program. Email: trakers@warsawschools.org

shared_text:
Warsaw Community Schools added 4 new photos.
March 12 at 1:20 PM ·

Minds in Motion provides children in schools with the physiological foundation they need to reach their full academic potential. Today, 16 WCS teachers learned why movement and physical activity are critical for all students’ success.

Minds-in-Motion has assimilated years of reading intervention experience, critical research on brain function, training with key neuro-development professionals, and compilation of scientific data to create an educationally published “comprehensive movement program that integrates the brain & body,emphasizing the physiological link between learning and movement.”

WCS has many elementary schools currently providing this program daily in their buildings. Staff attending today are learning the "Why do we do this?" and "What do we do?" from Matt Martin, trainer. Maria Demopoulos, Autism Resource Specialist, added, "Our hope is for WCS to bring this program back to their buildings to then expand providing this to any and all the kids that need this activity in their day to be successful."

Announcement: WCHS will host their annual Academic Super Bowl Invitational on Monday, March 9 from 5:30 to 9 PM. 14 area high schools will compete.

This year’s theme is the "Roaring Twenties.” Students have their knowledge tested on content from that time period in the subjects of Math, English, Science, Fine Arts, and Social Studies with an Interdisciplinary round at the end of the evening.

Warsaw Community High School has 25 student competitors and six coaches. The Academic Superbowl Coordinator for WCHS is Christine Smith. The event’s emcee is Class of 2021 Assistant Principal Stephen Clark. Results will be posted on wchs.warsawschools.org

Lakeview Middle School will host an Art Show & Sale on Sunday, March 22, 2020, from 2 PM to 4 PM at Lakeview Middle School Cafeteria.
This is a Cash & Carry event with 60% of proceeds benefiting student artists. 20% will help support local student art enrichment opportunities.
Another 20% will go toward The Riley Cheer Guild Art Cart supporting Art Therapy. Art Therapy is a mental health profession that uses the creative process of art-making to improve and enhance the physical, mental and emotional well-being of individuals of all ages.
Don't miss this opportunity to support local student artists and Riley Hospital for Children on Sunday, March 22nd, 2020!

post_text:
Suzie Light, Kosciusko County Community Foundation’s CEO, was recognized at the Warsaw Community School Board Meeting on Monday, February 24.

Dani Barkey, Assistant Superintendent of Secondary Schools, highlighted Suzie Light’s contributions to Warsaw Community Schools and presented Suzie with a basket brimming with a gift from each of the district’s schools.

With season tickets to Athletic events as well as a lifetime membership to the Performing Arts Center, Suzie will continue to be a familiar face. Also gifted were various apparel items so Suzie can bring her school spirit when she’s cheering on her Tigers on the field! This token of appreciation comes with an open invitation and expectation that Suzie will continue to plug-in with us and remain an important part of the WCS story.

Thank you Suzie Light for all you have given to our schools and our community! #wcsmission

Check out the JUST Published Video: Abbi Richcreek, Project Lead the Way Teacher at Edgewood Middle School in Warsaw, IN, received the PATINS Project Starfish Award in January 2020 for her innovative extracurricular program in conjunction with the Go Baby Go Program which provides modified, ride-on cars to young children with disabilities so they can move, play, and socialize with their peers independently. Through the after school program run by Abbi, teams of middle school students work with local engineers/mentors to redesign a car for a selected toddler to meet his or her specific needs. She was nominated by parent Elizabeth Hausmann on behalf of her daughter, Addy. #wcsmission
VIDEO: http://bit.ly/arichcreek

Las Escuelas de la Comunidad de Warsaw invitan a todas las partes interesadas, incluyendo a la comunidad, los padres, el personal y los estudiantes a participar en una encuesta para informar el plan estratégico de la corporación escolar para los próximos cinco años.

Las respuestas son confidenciales y la participación es voluntaria. Hay una opción para realizar la encuesta en inglés o en español y se espera que tome aproximadamente 5 minutos. Las primeras 3 preguntas establecen la demografía, mientras que las preguntas 4-9 permiten una oportunidad para construir una visión compartida para el futuro éxito de los estudiantes. La encuesta se cerrará el jueves 27 de febrero a las 5:00 PM.

Las Escuelas de la Comunidad de Warsaw quieren agradecerle por su tiempo y talentos para lanzar esta iniciativa que informará el próximo plan estratégico quinquenal de la corporación escolar.

Warsaw Community Schools invites all stakeholders, including community, parents, staff, and students to participate in a survey to inform the school corporation’s next five-year strategic plan.

Responses are confidential and participation is voluntary. There is an option to take the survey in English or in Spanish and it is expected to take approximately 5 minutes. The first 3 questions establish demographics, while questions 4-9 allow for an opportunity to build a shared vision for the future success of students. The survey will close on Thursday, February 27 at 5:00 PM.

Warsaw Community Schools would like to thank you for your time and talents to launch this initiative that will inform the school corporation’s next five-year strategic plan.

SURVEY LINK: http://bit.ly/wcsstrategicsurvey

The WCHS Drama Department presents its 3rd Annual Disney Character Day on Feb. 8 from 12:00 to 3:00 PM in the Performing Arts Center.

All children will be able to do crafts with the characters and have photo opportunities with characters.There will also be coloring stations and cookies available. A regular priced ticket of $10.00 per child includes all of these activities.

A VIP ticket of $15.00 per child includes all of the above plus a makeover from 12:00 to 3:00 PM and a special photo opportunity from 2 PM to 3 PM with Cinderella, the Prince, and the coach.

Tickets are available at the door or by calling the box office at (574) 371-5040
